{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17468895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17468895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:25:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:25:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"23"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480187"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"23"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/23"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.02,0.03,0.52,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"23"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57930"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/23"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"23"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41957"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57930"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 89-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after an episode of syncope while climbing stairs. He felt dizzy and sweaty immediately before the episode. He reports 10-minute episodes of exertional chest pain over the past few days. He has experienced increasing breathlessness on exertion and bilateral leg swelling over the past few weeks. He has no palpitations, nausea or vomiting. His medical history includes aortic stenosis, hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include hydrochlorothiazide and rosuvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale. His vital signs are within normal limits. Cardiovascular examination reveals a loud systolic ejection murmur maximal in the right second intercostal space. There are fine basal crepitations on chest auscultation and bilateral pitting ankle oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms indicates the poorest prognosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leg swelling","Dizziness","Sweating","Syncope","Exertional chest pain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple symptoms of severe aortic stenosis complicated by heart failure. The classic triad of symptoms in aortic stenosis consists of angina, syncope and dyspnoea. While all symptoms indicate severe disease requiring intervention, the presence of heart failure carries the worst prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeg swelling\u003C/strong\u003E in this context represents right heart failure, which indicates end-stage disease and carries the poorest prognosis. The development of heart failure symptoms suggests the left ventricle can no longer compensate for the severe outflow obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDizziness\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to reduced cerebral perfusion when cardiac output cannot increase to meet demands, particularly during exertion. While concerning, it does not necessarily indicate end-stage disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESweating\u003C/strong\u003E commonly accompanies exertional symptoms in aortic stenosis but is a non-specific finding that does not independently predict prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyncope\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to inability to maintain cerebral perfusion during exertion when peripheral vasodilation occurs. While it indicates severe disease, prognosis can improve with valve replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExertional chest pain\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to supply-demand mismatch causing subendocardial ischaemia. Like syncope, while it indicates severe disease requiring intervention, prognosis improves with appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Heart failure symptoms in aortic stenosis indicate a poor prognosis and need for urgent intervention","The classic triad of aortic stenosis symptoms are angina, syncope, and dyspnoea","Development of any symptoms in aortic stenosis indicates need for valve replacement assessment"],"references":["Gotzmann M, Rahlmann P, Hehnen T, M\u00fcller P, Lindstaedt M, et al. Heart failure in severe aortic valve stenosis: prognostic impact of left ventricular ejection fraction and mean gradient on outcome after transcatheter aortic valve implantation. Eur J Heart Fail. 2012;14(10):1155-62. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1093/eurjhf/hfs108","Frank S, Johnson A, Ross J Jr. Natural history of valvular aortic stenosis. Br Heart J. 1973;35(1):41-46. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC458562/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"23"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T08:48:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T15:45:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"23"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57930"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags